If Georges Rouault is the twentieth century's religious painter, par excellence, it is certainly not in the usual sense of a depictor of religious themes, although these constitute a large part of his oeuvre. Rather, it is his profound spiritual melancholy with the things of this world, vs. a luminous hope of things to come, that place himâ€”despite the utter modernity of his Expressionist technique-squarely in the tradition of the medieval artist
